Note:
Runtime reader-writer lock API — the public shared/exclusive synchronization
object for the Runa runtime concurrency system.

This is the runtime-facing object layer. The actual locking mechanism is the
completed cross-platform synchronization facade (sync_core), which itself
delegates to the per-architecture OS rwlock / futex primitives. This module
does NOT re-implement locking; it wraps the sync_core rwlock handle in a
runtime RuntimeRwLock object and adds the semantics a runtime contract requires
that the raw facade does not provide:

  - SHARED VS EXCLUSIVE ACCESS: many readers may hold the lock concurrently
    (read acquire) while a writer requires exclusive ownership (write acquire).
    The facade enforces the actual reader/writer arbitration; this layer
    exposes it through a single, documented status contract.
  - POISONING: a holder that detects an unrecoverable error in the data it is
    protecting marks the lock poisoned. Subsequent acquirers (readers or
    writers) still obtain the lock — access is still needed to inspect or
    repair the data — but are told RWLOCK_ERR_POISONED so they can decide
    whether to recover or abort. This mirrors the poison model used by mature
    systems runtimes and is the standard way to surface "a previous critical
    section left this state inconsistent" without unwinding.
  - STANDARDIZED STATUS CODES: every entry point returns an RWLOCK_* status so
    callers branch on a single, documented contract rather than the facade's
    raw 1/0 platform results.

RuntimeRwLock layout (16 bytes):
    offset 0:  handle    — the sync_core rwlock_ptr (the real lock)
    offset 8:  poisoned  — 0 healthy, 1 poisoned
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/threading/sync_core.runa" as Sync
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory

Note: RuntimeRwLock object layout
Constant RT_RWLOCK_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant RT_RWLOCK_OFF_HANDLE as Integer is 0
Constant RT_RWLOCK_OFF_POISONED as Integer is 8

Note: Status codes returned by the runtime reader-writer lock API
Constant RWLOCK_OK as Integer is 0
Constant RWLOCK_ERR_NULL as Integer is 0 minus 1
Constant RWLOCK_ERR_POISONED as Integer is 0 minus 2
Constant RWLOCK_ERR_LOCK_FAILED as Integer is 0 minus 3
Constant RWLOCK_ERR_BUSY as Integer is 0 minus 4

Process called "rwlock_new" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a runtime reader-writer lock object. Mechanism (the OS shared/
    exclusive lock) comes from sync_core; this layer adds the poison flag and a
    stable object identity callers hold.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate the 16-byte RuntimeRwLock, create the underlying sync_core rwlock,
    store its handle, and initialize the poison flag to healthy (0). On any
    allocation/creation failure, release whatever was acquired and return 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One small allocation plus one sync_core rwlock_create (which allocates its
    own 24-byte control block and an OS rwlock). Cold path: done once per lock.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Failure returns 0 (NULL); callers MUST check before use.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let r be proc allocate from Memory with RT_RWLOCK_SIZE
    If r is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let handle be proc rwlock_create from Sync
    If handle is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with r
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with r, RT_RWLOCK_OFF_HANDLE, handle
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with r, RT_RWLOCK_OFF_POISONED, 0
    Return r
End Process

Process called "rwlock_read_acquire" takes r as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Block until shared (read) access is held, then report whether the protected
    state is trustworthy. The lock is acquired even when poisoned because the
    caller still needs access to inspect or repair the inconsistent data.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate the blocking shared acquire to sync_core rwlock_read_lock. A result
    other than 1 means the lock is NOT held and we return RWLOCK_ERR_LOCK_FAILED.
    Once held, return RWLOCK_ERR_POISONED when the poison flag is set (the lock
    is still held and must be released), otherwise RWLOCK_OK.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core rwlock_read_lock (fast user-space path uncontended; OS wait
    only when a writer holds or is queued) plus two field loads.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns RWLOCK_ERR_NULL without touching memory. When RWLOCK_OK
    or RWLOCK_ERR_POISONED is returned the lock IS held and the caller owns the
    obligation to release it.
    @End Security_Scope

    If r is equal to 0:
        Return RWLOCK_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with r, RT_RWLOCK_OFF_HANDLE
    Let result be proc rwlock_read_lock from Sync with handle
    If result is not equal to 1:
        Return RWLOCK_ERR_LOCK_FAILED
    End If

    Let poisoned be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with r, RT_RWLOCK_OFF_POISONED
    If poisoned is not equal to 0:
        Return RWLOCK_ERR_POISONED
    End If
    Return RWLOCK_OK
End Process

Process called "rwlock_try_read_acquire" takes r as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking shared acquire for callers that must make progress rather than
    wait for a writer to release.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to sync_core rwlock_try_read_lock. A result other than 1 means a
    writer holds (or is being granted) the lock, so we return RWLOCK_ERR_BUSY.
    On success, surface poison state exactly as rwlock_read_acquire does so the
    held/poison contract is identical on both paths.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core rwlock_try_read_lock (single attempt, never blocks) plus field
    loads.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns RWLOCK_ERR_NULL. The lock is held only when RWLOCK_OK or
    RWLOCK_ERR_POISONED is returned.
    @End Security_Scope

    If r is equal to 0:
        Return RWLOCK_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with r, RT_RWLOCK_OFF_HANDLE
    Let result be proc rwlock_try_read_lock from Sync with handle
    If result is not equal to 1:
        Return RWLOCK_ERR_BUSY
    End If

    Let poisoned be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with r, RT_RWLOCK_OFF_POISONED
    If poisoned is not equal to 0:
        Return RWLOCK_ERR_POISONED
    End If
    Return RWLOCK_OK
End Process

Process called "rwlock_write_acquire" takes r as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Block until exclusive (write) access is held, then report whether the
    protected state is trustworthy. Exclusive access excludes all other readers
    and writers for the duration the lock is held.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate the blocking exclusive acquire to sync_core rwlock_write_lock. A
    result other than 1 means the lock is NOT held and we return
    RWLOCK_ERR_LOCK_FAILED. Once held, return RWLOCK_ERR_POISONED when the
    poison flag is set (the lock is still held and must be released), otherwise
    RWLOCK_OK.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core rwlock_write_lock (fast user-space path uncontended; OS wait
    while readers or another writer hold) plus two field loads.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns RWLOCK_ERR_NULL without touching memory. When RWLOCK_OK
    or RWLOCK_ERR_POISONED is returned the lock IS held exclusively and the
    caller owns the obligation to release it.
    @End Security_Scope

    If r is equal to 0:
        Return RWLOCK_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with r, RT_RWLOCK_OFF_HANDLE
    Let result be proc rwlock_write_lock from Sync with handle
    If result is not equal to 1:
        Return RWLOCK_ERR_LOCK_FAILED
    End If

    Let poisoned be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with r, RT_RWLOCK_OFF_POISONED
    If poisoned is not equal to 0:
        Return RWLOCK_ERR_POISONED
    End If
    Return RWLOCK_OK
End Process

Process called "rwlock_try_write_acquire" takes r as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking exclusive acquire for callers that must make progress rather
    than wait for readers or another writer to release.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to sync_core rwlock_try_write_lock. A result other than 1 means the
    lock is currently held by readers or another writer, so we return
    RWLOCK_ERR_BUSY. On success, surface poison state exactly as
    rwlock_write_acquire does so the held/poison contract is identical on both
    paths.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core rwlock_try_write_lock (single attempt, never blocks) plus
    field loads.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns RWLOCK_ERR_NULL. The lock is held exclusively only when
    RWLOCK_OK or RWLOCK_ERR_POISONED is returned.
    @End Security_Scope

    If r is equal to 0:
        Return RWLOCK_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with r, RT_RWLOCK_OFF_HANDLE
    Let result be proc rwlock_try_write_lock from Sync with handle
    If result is not equal to 1:
        Return RWLOCK_ERR_BUSY
    End If

    Let poisoned be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with r, RT_RWLOCK_OFF_POISONED
    If poisoned is not equal to 0:
        Return RWLOCK_ERR_POISONED
    End If
    Return RWLOCK_OK
End Process

Process called "rwlock_release" takes r as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release a held lock, whether it was acquired for shared (read) or exclusive
    (write) access. Must be called exactly once per successful acquire
    (including the RWLOCK_ERR_POISONED acquire, which still holds the lock).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to sync_core rwlock_unlock, which decrements the reader count or
    clears the writer-owner tracking and releases the OS lock as appropriate.
    Return RWLOCK_OK on success.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core rwlock_unlock (user-space update on the uncontended path; a
    wake of waiting readers or a writer when present).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns RWLOCK_ERR_NULL. Releasing a lock not held by the caller
    is a logic error surfaced by the underlying facade.
    @End Security_Scope

    If r is equal to 0:
        Return RWLOCK_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with r, RT_RWLOCK_OFF_HANDLE
    proc rwlock_unlock from Sync with handle
    Return RWLOCK_OK
End Process

Process called "rwlock_is_poisoned" takes r as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report whether a previous critical section flagged the protected data as
    inconsistent.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the poison flag (1 poisoned, 0 healthy).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure read.
    @End Security_Scope

    If r is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with r, RT_RWLOCK_OFF_POISONED
End Process

Process called "rwlock_poison" takes r as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Mark the lock poisoned. A holder that detects an unrecoverable failure in
    the protected state calls this before releasing so later acquirers are
    warned the data may be inconsistent.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Set the poison flag to 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field store.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Should be called while holding the lock (ideally a write acquire) so the
    flag is published before the next acquirer observes it.
    @End Security_Scope

    If r is equal to 0:
        Return RWLOCK_ERR_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with r, RT_RWLOCK_OFF_POISONED, 1
    Return RWLOCK_OK
End Process

Process called "rwlock_clear_poison" takes r as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Clear the poison flag after a caller has repaired the protected state,
    returning the lock to normal service.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Set the poison flag to 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field store.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Should be called while holding the lock for exclusive (write) access, after
    the inconsistent state has actually been repaired.
    @End Security_Scope

    If r is equal to 0:
        Return RWLOCK_ERR_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with r, RT_RWLOCK_OFF_POISONED, 0
    Return RWLOCK_OK
End Process

Process called "rwlock_destroy" takes r as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the OS lock and free the runtime object. Must not be called while
    the lock is held by any reader or writer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to sync_core rwlock_destroy (which frees the facade control block
    and the OS rwlock), then deallocate the RuntimeRwLock object.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core rwlock_destroy plus one deallocate. Cold path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns RWLOCK_ERR_NULL. Destroying a held lock is a logic error.
    @End Security_Scope

    If r is equal to 0:
        Return RWLOCK_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with r, RT_RWLOCK_OFF_HANDLE
    proc rwlock_destroy from Sync with handle
    proc deallocate from Memory with r
    Return RWLOCK_OK
End Process
